AKI Project - CatBoost Method¶

Introduction¶

  • Acute Kidney Injury (AKI)
    • A clinical syndrome characterized by the rapid (hours to days) loss of the kidney’s excretory function.
    • Typically diagnosed by the accumulation of end products of nitrogen metabolism (urea and creatinine) or decreased urine output (not always present), or both.
    • 20%~50% overall incidences of AKI in ICU patients (Case et al., 2013)
    • Associated with mortality greater than 50% (Case et al., 2013)

                                        Conceptual model for AKI (Murray et al, 2008)

  • We are going to use KDIGO Clinical Practice Guidelines for Acute Kidney Injury (AKI).
    1. Increase in serum creatinine by $\geq$0.3 mg/dl within 48h
    2. Increase in serum creatinine to $\geq$1.5 times baseline, which is known or presumed to have occurred within the prior 7 days
    3. Urine volume $\leq$0.5 ml/kg/h for 6h

We are going to use the first one of KDIGO Clinical Practice Guidelines for AKI.

Handling class imbalance¶

  • Using balanced class weight
    • Adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies in the input data
  • Resampling
    • Over-sampling
      • Increase the number of instances from minority class
    • Under-sampling
      • Decrease the number of instances from majority class
    • Combine oversampling and under-sampling
  • Over-sampling
In [84]:

CatBoost: gradient boosting with categorical features support¶

CatBoost is a state-of-the-art open-source gradient boosting on decision tree library.

Developed by Yandex researchers and engineers, it is the successor of the MatrixNet algorithm that is wisely used within the company for ranking tasks, forecasting and making recommendations. It is universal and can be applied across a wide range of areas and to a variety of problems.

Shap values¶

SHAP Values (an acronym from SHapley Additive exPlanations) break down a prediction to show the impact of each feature.

  • A model says a bank shouldn't loan someone money, and the bank is legally required to explain the basis for each loan rejection
  • A healthcare provider wants to identify what factors are driving each patient's risk of some disease so they can directly address those risk factors with targeted health interventions
